segments.text: I think if I did anything as far as the staff is concerned, I delegated much more.
Frank was not about to delegate anything.
Yeah, and I don't think that was peculiar to his experience at A&M.
I think he operated the same way in Texas.
I know in Texas he went through sales managers like a change in socks, and that was partly because there was always, you know,
Yeah, Don Collins is there.
When you arrived, or about the same, he arrived about the same time.
He must have been ahead of me.
They were all there when I arrived.
Yeah, Naylor and Norm and Don.
But I didn't know if you'd actually gotten to see them.
Oh, yes.
And Ray Gamaya.
Gamaya, yeah, was there.
Yes.
They were all there.
The only person that I hired of the...
Latin group was first was MaryLynn Dixon, and the other was Jim Billingsley when Vermila died.
Yeah.
I just interviewed Billingsley.
Is that right?
He was coming to town.
I was going to go to him, but...
In Knoxville, yeah.
But he was coming in and called me just by chance, said, I'm coming to town.
I said, well, you're just in time.
I've been thinking about you.
He left very embittered, crusty.
He came there crusty and embittered.
I liked it.
He and I got along real well.
I had him do some book designs for me.
I was going to say, what on earth was he doing back there?
I can't imagine.
I don't know.
He came to see his neighbors, I think.
He didn't even want to go to the press.
I told him he was coming.
The lady who took his place.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Yeah, the one that worked for Caleb.
Not Susan.
No, not the other one.
Anyway, Linda?
Anyway, she kind of apparently corralled him and did get him to come up, and I'm glad they did.
He should be there.
And visit around.
And their car had broken down.
So you're... Those were the only two people that I replaced from the original staff.
Okay.
And now...
One thing that really struck me interesting is that almost from the time he arrived, Wardlaw was talking retirement.
Yes, that was part of the theory.
That really startled me, yeah.
Oh, no, that was part of the deal, Henry.
He was expecting to retire all the time.
And I cannot remember whether there was health problems involved.
Well, he had constantly.
Oh, he lived stuff.
He always had something wrong.
Yeah.
something natural or something he invoked by going to Mexico or wherever it was.
I remember he came back from one Mexico trip.
Oh yeah, well he got Montezuma's revenge in a big way on one of those.
He traveled around with August Frugge and Chester Kerr.
They were on a committee for the National
Association, and they went and established outlets.
They went to South America at least twice, once to just Central America and South America.

Once they went all over South America trying to arrange distribution because, you know, the tariff businesses in Brazil and all of it were just terrible, and they were trying to get some, they were trying to find a central distributor, and they ended up working out of Mexico.
lasted for a while.
But they also went to Mexico two or three times.
Of course, he liked that.
Yeah, yeah.
And they, the other two, all three of them had big lists of South American stuff.
California, Texas, and Yale.
All three had big, that's how they got on that committee.
But they also were longtime
So, Wardlaw, let's get to Wardlaw's retirement.
I guess there's something in that context that you think is notable.
No, he planned, that was the whole business of introducing me to all these people.
Now, there was a big to-do about the retirement, as I recall.

there must have been but you know i can't recall you did a lot you had a lot to do with it and it seemed to me in terms of the uh preparing for preparing for you know kind of a well i'll tell you i don't remember as much anything about that nearly as what i remember about his his funeral yeah right now that was big yeah we'll hold that yeah and get to that i don't i don't recall i remember some dinners yeah maybe that was all some of the conventional dinners but i don't um
By that time, Jack Williams was not there.
Okay, let's get to that point right now.
Wardlaw retired in 78, I believe.
That sounds about right.
And you became director.
Yes, I think that was from 78 to 88.
And Jack was still in hand.
He had become chancellor.
He had become chancellor, yes.
Now, was the press under the chancellor or the president?
I'm trying to remember myself now.
I believe that Williams took the press with him.
I think he did, too.

did take the press with him okay so so you're reporting to jack williams yes as a director yes and and there is a good accord good relationship with jack williams absolutely it was it was indispensable at that point and now that's 78. i guess the first step is within six months of your becoming director the press building burned yes
In connection with this business of the reporting, when Vandiver came in, I think that's when I was supposed to report to the President rather than the Chancellor again.
Oh, okay.
I think that was it.
It may havewas there a teacher?
There wasn't a professor for Vandiver, it was Miller, but who was it?
Frank Hubert was it?
No, wait.
Well, as a matter of fact, Clyde Wells was an interim for a short time.
That's when it changed, when I started reporting to the president.
I must have reported to Miller.
I'll find out.
I don't know exactly how that went, but I don't recall.
Times were very confusing in that shuffle.
That's kind of what I was... Yeah, it was very confusing.
And also very hazardous to the health of the press, perhaps.
Did you sense anything?
any problems there.
Well, now, when this came, when did it come, when did that, the second infusion of cash from the Regents?
That was during...
Warden Law was gone by then.
Yeah, that was, I think in... And we needed $20,000 or something of that sort, and we got it, but nobody expected us to get it.
And Frank was very upset and worried about the

financial he was yes he was and i have some letters from him written to me from rice as i recall right after the fire yeah and he was very concerned about the press and then in fact you and uh warren law responded with letters to wells and williams or someone else saying no this is we were not that desperate things are okay we're going to make that we're going to get through this
But Frank may have been useful in triggering a sense of alarm.
And I wondered about this.
If that conceivably began to catch the region's attention for a moment, that maybe they'd better deal with this situation.
Because apparently they were not interested in dealing with it directly.
It just sprang out of the earth, it seemed to, as far as I was concerned.
I don't remember any advance warning about the damn thing.

yeah i'll go to hubert and see if hubert would yeah he's he's crucial to this yeah uh but that's i that's what i felt like a really stormy difficult time and i hadn't really appreciated it until i started looking into this frank wrote me a very depressing letter maybe yes i saw that letter yeah yeah where i would just have to pull in our i'd have to pull in my horns and yeah tough it out yeah yeah

people were very depressed and this was a really tough you know and he communicated that he wrote that same letter sent copies of it or something to half the world oh yes yeah and then several regions responded directly to him he sent a copy of it to joe and betty moore he sent a copy of it to pride wells he sent it to a lot of people that's what they did and
That may have.
I was really wondering about that.
But the response to that letter was, no, these things are not that bad at all, Frank.
You don't understand.
But, you know, that could have been a trigger, and I've always wondered about that.
That's another thing about Frank.
He let you know just what you needed to know, period.
Yeah.
He never expanded or explained.
It was forward march.
So Wardlaw retires.
You're in control.
Do you have any special change of direction or policies?
No.
One of the things that you're in charge of the press.
Basically, your charge is to continue to thrust the direction of the Texas A&M University Press as it has been established by Frank Wardlaw.
In fact, I would argue that you were not given a lot of options because of the character of the funding.
This is one of the things that I'm following.
That's correct.
That Wardlaw really defined things.
Yeah, the logic of the financial logic determined the direction.
That's right.
And he knew it, I think.
Well, and it wasn't a bad direction.
No, no.
In fact, I think one of the things that happened
briefly during my time there, was that A&M preempted the regional publishing material.
I remember, what's the guy that runs the Texas State Historical?
Tuffy, Tuffy Ellis.
No, who's Tuffy Ellis's successor?
I remember Ron Tyler saying to me once that every time he looked for a manuscript, he found out that Texas A&M had already been there.
And that during that time, for a while there,
Texas A&M got a lot of the Texas Institute of Letters awards, and that was sort of a peak moment, which disappeared almost once as I disappeared.
I don't know that that was, but that was a... Now, let's briefly look at the fire, because shortly after you became... That was the first really big crisis, yes.
And that occurred what day?
Do you remember?
It's deeply in your mind.
Not today, but the occasion I can remember.
We got a phone call.
The phone rang in the very early morning.
It said the building was burning.
I don't know who it was.
The Williamses were still in their apartment, weren't they, at that point, I think.
Yes.
And was Buck Shewitt still living in the building?
No.
Okay, he had left.
I know there was no mention of him.
No, it was the Williams were living in the apartment at the time.
And the students came in and helped haul stuff out of their apartment, mainly, but the upstairs was gone.
It started above the press offices, basically.
As I remember, there was some repair work going on, and somebody left an electric light
Oh, okay.
A big light, I don't know, 200, 300 watts or something.
They put material over it, and it caught on fire and blew it.
And the reason they got out as much stuff as was gotten out was that it burned down from the top.
It didn't come up from the bottom.
And they got to it in time.
One of the things that was very lucky was that very little of the important
records were lost.
We got out almost, the loss of any records, any files was, you know.
The roof literally fell on your desk and file cabinets, and that helped.
Yeah, that collapsed, that's right, yeah, especially in that big room, in the big meeting room, and I think in my office, and all over.
So when you arrived, it's burning.
Yes, and I encountered
President Miller, who was also there.
And he was upset.
OK. And after the fire, the press is going to resume its duties in the garage, basically, which is the storeroom.
Well, it was also a portable.
There was a portable trailer that was moved in.
to the site at the press building?
I didn't remember the trailer there.
I remember the trailers y'all moved into later, but at first you started off in the garage.
Well, not very long.
Those buildings, those portable buildings were in there behind where the original...
There were two of those.
There were two.
They were joined together.
You must have been in those.
Oh, yeah, I was in those.
And across the street, there was a garage, and this is where...
There was a, we had a lot of books that we brought in instead of having to go out to the place on the highway.
It's where the nautical archaeology was, the annex.
Riverside campus, they call it now.
Oh, okay.
That's where the major storage area was, but we also had this...
place right across the street where they could do packing.
Now, after the fire, what was the initial administrative reaction or involvement or situation?
I do remember, and I think I mentioned this to you yesterday, of having a visitation
from one of the regents and one of the officers of the administration.
I don't recall who it was.
I don't believe it.
It was not the president.
But they came and told me that the likelihood of a new building was very slight.
This was typical for university presses.
University presses have
rarely gotten a new building.
Most university presses have made do with basement offices, abandoned academic offices or buildings that have been originally intended for something else entirely.
How did the thrust in for new buildings begin?
As far as I know,
It was Frank.
It was Hubert's.
He's the one that thrust it.
It just seemed to have, it appeared almost out of the blue, as far as I was concerned.
I had almost no advance notice.

I interviewed Hubert for something, oh, I guess it was this pictorial thing, and he told me how that had, how he became, they had just asked him to come up, and he said, I thought I was going up to advise him on,

what to do and they said they asked him to be the acting whatever it was president he said that was a surprise to me you know he's brilliant understates everything but apparently he really was surprised he had no information at all they were even thinking and i guess he was just well known well respected he was a good stable ballroom person well he certainly was good to to the press
So, okay, I'm going to get to him on the building and the funding.

And the building, yeah, and the other thing about the building that I remember was that they put it out for bids, and I don't recall who got the bid, but they constructed the, or they laid out the design for the building, and the regent said that was not satisfactory.
And you look at that building now, and it's,
It was originally designed for all of the offices' spaces to be on the perimeter with a patio in the middle.
And one of the regents, and I don't remember which one, refused to waste that much space in a building on space that could not be used for anything, just for looks.
And so at the last minute, they dumped the original design

and they took one of the employees of the buildings and grounds his first name was bob and i don't remember what his last name is but he essentially redesigned the building and that's what is the result now that bullpen that exists in the middle now we're all where the the building shipping and building people all sit that was that was supposed to be the patio patio was open to the sky
And there was going to be more offices back toward the warehouse structure.
I don't remember exactly how it all looked, but it was going to be a whole thing.
And the library was another area that Bob just completely did over on the spur of the moment.
It isn't a bad-looking building now, but it could have been spectacular.
It was unique at the time.
I mean, it got a lot of attention among other university presses because there were very few, like I say, that had their own building.
The dedication was in 1983.
When was that finished?
Do you remember by any chance?
The fire is in, whatever it was, December, oh, I can't remember, February of, February of 79?
No, no, that's wrong.
I believe that's right, I don't know.
Yeah, I don't remember how long we were in those graves.
The dedication was 83.
83, yeah.
Well, we were in the building.
You were there.
We were in the building when the dedication, before the dedication.
Yeah, I think you were there, but I don't remember.
I want to check that.
Yeah.
But you were in those trailers then for about two years.
We must have been in the trailers for a couple of years.
I'll check those.
I've got all of them.
Then on the, I don't know if it was even worth pursuing, there was a big move to, and I know how I knew him, to name the building for Frank Wardlaw.
And I've got all the literature on there.
And then letters were being circulated.
John Lindsay wrote a letter in favor of naming the building for Frank Wardlaw.
You know that?
No.
I never saw any of that.
Yeah.
And then there was a letter from someone to Clyde Wells.
Clyde Wells said, I'm sorry, we have already made that decision.
It's not going to be named for Frank Wardlaw.
There was a letter somewhere, or at least there was pressure applied by Ford Albridge
who lobbied very hard for John Lindsay.
Yeah, and I don't know if it's really out of the blue, you know, you don't know how much Lindsay knew, but there is a, anyway, it was very clear the regents had already decided.
And all that was going on outside of their whatever, and then, you know, it's a done deal.
Yes, I don't know, but I know that Auburn was very, very,
active in wanting names or anything.
And these were, you know, former, this is kind of a former student trust.
What was your relationship, incidentally, to the former students as director?
Only... How about Buck Weir, specifically?
He was very helpful, yes.
Yeah.
Yeah, yeah.
He was, as long as he was there, well, even after
It was always very cordial, but there was no, I don't recall that there was any... How about Jerry Cooper with the Texas Aggie magazine?
Yes, we always had, he was frequently advertised or ran items about in the press.
Is he still there?
Yeah.
You know that book that we did, The Walking Soul?
Yes.

I kept trying to get Yama to sell a pedalette in a football game, and she said, we can't do that because they want the, you know, whoever runs the football game, they want those out competing with their program.
That was amazing.
So you've got the building drive development program going on from 79 to 83, roughly.
You've got the naming thing going on.
Now, what about publishing?
What books?
What's happening in the world of publishing?
I'm trying to think of the titles that appeared to me.
I should have brought that list.
I didn't.
I had to.
That's okay.
But I just thought maybe there's some titles or events or things that you particularly...
The books that I do remember... Yeah, tell me about the books you remember, because that's what I wanted to do, is just spot some things.
When did the...
I'll go up and look at the...
I still have the book.
The Cowboy Life on the Texas Plains, Marge Rector's book with John... Just tell me about things that you remember.
that were particularly interesting and significant.
Well, another thing that I remember, and I think it was during the same time as this, H.W.
Kaler, the Big Springs Museum book that did Kaler's paintings.
We went, they provided the funds for that.
Is that the blue?
That's okay.
No, I get it.
That's okay.
I get it.
It's not big deal.
Okay.
the variety, the directors.

I remember we went, I can remember especially going to Rice University, which no longer has a press, I understand, but at the time, that's the first time I'd ever been on the Rice campus, and we went to see all the administrators, and they, I got to wind and dine in their faculty club, and they,
came aboard, and the first editor.
Was Frank there then?
Wardlow?
No, no, Vandiver.
I think Vandiver.
I'll check my dates too, but I think he may still be a prologist, wasn't he?
May have been, yes.
He could have put the lean on them.
I'll go talk to Frank.
I saw him the other day and just chatted, but I didn't really... My impression on that, Henry, is that he had little or nothing to do with it.
There was Bill...
Who was the lieutenant governor?
Barnes.
No, no.
There was a lieutenant governor that had, for a long time, lieutenant governor.
He never ran for governor.
Bill... Wasn't Bill Barnes?
No, no, no, no.
Anyway, his life was very busy with the press.
And he had influence.
I think he was already some kind of a factotum at Rice.
And she had a lot to do, or I had the impression that she had a lot to do with agreeing to become a part of the distribution.
And we also approached the University of Texas.
There was no response.
Basically, what happened is
This is your plan.
You're going to offer them the opportunity to distribute through Texas A&M.
And so you look at all of the presses in Texas and you go to them, basically, and say, here's what we can do for you.
Now, who is going with you in this?
Collins, or Shira, or Noel, or anybody, or just yourself?
I think, for the most part, it was just me.
And Gayle went to some of these.
Maybe Collins went on some of these.
Collins certainly got into it as soon as they started doing something serious.
And I met all of them.
The guy at El Paso, Texas Tech, SMU, TCU, Waco, Baylor.
We fiddled around with Baylor.
I don't remember what that came to, but... Because I really think that's a big, that's a really significant...
It worked out very well.
To me it made sense to have the cooperation.
I don't know why Texas couldn't have.
Because it's a central, and especially now with this all computerized, the more computerized it gets, who gives a hoot
Where it's being mailed from.
Yeah, and all together, if you save, you do make.
Even giving A&M a percent, you save.
Oh, you bet.
Oh, there's no, yeah.
So that was really significant.
I wanted to try to flag that.
Well, that, yeah, you know, I never really, in thinking about it in retrospect, it is an important thing, but I never...
We were just doing it.
It seemed like we had a big empty warehouse, and this was a way to fill it up and also get some return for it.
And I'll go through and I'll pick up all that we've signed on.
Yeah, yeah.
Any other recall about that process?
I can't think, the one that I remember seeing, I was seeing Dick, or Gregory, not Dick Gregory, but Keith, and the people at Tech fairly often anyway.
And it was just, sometimes it was social matter almost.
Which sure makes a lot of sense.
Okay, so this is the advisory council, which was one of the things that Frank set up just before he left.
Yes, and I probably did not utilize that as much as I should have, principally because I was not well acquainted with very many of them, and I felt reticent, and that was one of the
mistakes that I made would be discussed, that we mentioned yesterday, about Moshe.
If I had known him better, I would have not hesitated to barge in and talk to him.
And I regret that.
Thinking back, that's one of my biggest regrets.
Was there a scheduled annual meeting?
A regular, yes, it was regularly scheduled.
And that's John
as one of the longtime members and participants in that.
Now, was Haskell involved in any of that?
Yeah, I think he was.
Wasn't Haskell also chairman of the editorial committee?
Yes, he was chairman of the advisory committee, yeah.
Right.
For a long time, until he left, I guess.
Yeah, I think that's right.
Then Clint became.
Yes.

and they came in as the dean of faculties yeah you know that was their for their slot uh yeah and this was peculiar to a m because most uh editorial committees like the one that well let's say it this way the editorial committees that i was familiar with before the lsu and account these people there were all the members of the committee were selected or elected appointed usually by the faculty senate
And they elected their own chairman.
It wasn't a permanent slot.
And this had two things.
It was good one way and bad the other.
If you got a sympathetic person, it was good.
If you got an unsympathetic person, it was not so good.
Well, my inclination is that the press was very fortunate not to have gotten you in the faculty senate.
